A. Seven types of audits
B. Graduated confidence levels of evaluation
C. Seven security tools
D. Seven compliance laws

22. Moving from lower to higher assurance levels means:
A. Reduced scope
B. Increased depth and verification
C. Less control testing
D. Faster evaluation

23. Which assurance level would MOST likely include independent verification?
A. Lowest level
B. Medium level
C. Highest level
D. Informal level

24. Evaluation methodology should be selected based on:
A. Auditor preference
B. Organizational risk and compliance needs
C. Availability of tools
D. Budget only

25. A major limitation of low-assurance evaluation is:
A. High cost
B. Limited confidence and higher residual risk
C. Excessive documentation
D. Complex reporting

26. In evaluation phases, failure to define scope properly leads to:
A. Better coverage
B. Ineffective assurance results
C. Faster reporting
D. Improved confidence

27. Assurance levels are MOST useful when communicating results to:
A. Technical staff only
B. End users
C. Senior management and regulators
D. Vendors

28. Which activity differentiates evaluation from penetration testing?
A. Control testing
B. Assurance rating
C. Evidence collection
D. Reporting

29. Evaluation methodology enhances audit quality by ensuring:
A. Tool dependency
B. Consistent and objective assessment
C. Faster audits only
D. Reduced auditor involvement

30. A mature organization typically opts for higher assurance levels due to:
A. Compliance pressure and risk exposure
B. Reduced staff
C. Low threat landscape
D. No regulatory requirements

